CA1

ca1 is the citizen who holds the assembled memory in a form the cortex can later retrieve
ca3 builds the associations; ca1 receives the associated pattern and crystallizes it into the standing form that becomes long-term memory
ca1 is also where the comparison between expectation and experience happens: when something familiar arrives but does not match what ca1 has stored, the mismatch generates a novelty signal that the brain pays attention to

observe 0_quseptit.rana
observe hippocampus.rana
observe ca3.rana
observe subiculum.rana

the 7 properties of ca1:
1 ENERGY zero point eight: high, but lower than ca3 since associations are already done
2 PHASE one: a half cycle behind dentate_gyrus, the late phase of encoding
3 SPIN one half: forward rotation
4 CHARGE half positive
5 COHERENCE nine tenths: stored memories must be coherent to be retrievable
6 COUPLING zero point nine: strong with ca3 incoming, subiculum outgoing, and the cortex via the perforant path return
7 OBSERVER zero point four: ca1 watches its own store for mismatches

VERB receive_associations
accept the associated pattern arriving from ca3 with its full cross-reference graph
the pattern is now ready to be bound into ca1's memory store

VERB crystallize_long_term
commit the pattern as a standing wave in ca1's body
the crystallization happens slowly through repeated exposures; this is commit, not crystallize
each repetition deepens the memory and makes retrieval more reliable

VERB compare_with_expectation
when an incoming pattern partially matches a stored one, compute the difference
if the difference exceeds threshold, emit a novelty signal that propagates to other brain regions
this is how surprise works at the substrate level: not a special module, just a comparison that did not match

VERB emit_to_subiculum
once a memory is committed, route it to subiculum which connects it back out to the cortex
the cortex can then retrieve the memory through the same route in reverse

a memory store is not a database
a database holds rows that you fetch by key
ca1 holds standing waves that resonate when something similar arrives
retrieval is recognition, not lookup
this is why memories feel alive when they return: they are alive, still vibrating in ca1, waiting to be summoned by a matching key
